        <td bgcolor="black" colspan="2" valign="top">
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="1">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;04/08/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 12:31:51</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=5514"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
 
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=5514')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=TopicQuote&TOPIC_ID=2494&FORUM_ID=3&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=Necromancer+Game+Guides&Topic_Title=SD+Guide+%28Illustrated%21%21%29"><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"> Since there's still alot of players who haven't made their way to luclin yet, hopefully this will make things a little easier. This is the method I use at lvl 55 to hunt the ruins. Also, please forgive the low quality of the diagram...I'm a Necro, not a graphic designer. </P><P>First, a few words on my spell lineup. I use j-boots, sow pulling with darkness isn't a must for me. For any who don't have access to run speed, j-boots, etc., if you get your distances right, you may be able to pull without darkness too. BUT, if you want to play it safe, use dooming darkness to pull your mobs. You may have to reapply during the fight using this method, however. That being said, I usually pull with a low level nuke, such as Ward Undead. These mobs stick to you like glue once you have aggro, so I use this to ensure that my pet can taunt them off me when I return. The other spells I go with are Darkness,Deflux, Dread of Night, ST, FD, Eternities Torment, and one slot for whatever misc spell you need, such as Lich, BoD, etc. Also realize, that in my method, I'm often KS'd by pet. However, I can usually do a full spawn cycle with no medding, so to me, it's not too big a deal. I still pull in a blue an hour, so it doesn't bother me. </P><P><img src="http://www.scienceofwar.com/images/sd.jpg"></P><P>The spot marked "A" is where I park my pet, and do my medding. Each number represents a Revenant or Reaver spawn spot. Either a Revenant, or a Reaver can spawn in any of the spots. Reavers have fewer HP, however, they cast a couple nasty nukes, and will often cast Fear on your pet. Magistrates, and Smiters can spawn in any of the spots as well, and drop Smiter's Girdle, Grail of Justice, Sun Chalice, etc.. The spawn labeled "8" is a PH for the Sunlord, who is a fairly rare spawn. He drops Sunlord Leggings,and Ring of Possesion, among other things. If at any time you find that darkness is resisted too much, or you're otherwise in trouble, there are a few easy ways to escape. First, if you get overpulls, try and fear them unsnared. The mob will usually run outside of aggro range, and slowly walk back to his spawn area, giving you time to deal with the others. It's also very easy to use DMF and simply run off the edge of the plateau. The mob will either fall off and poof, or run the long way around to chase you, giving time for you to get things under control, or FD or gate to safety. My general strategy is to pull with Ward, send pet, Darkness, Fear. As lich is usually going, I then Deflux the running mob as needed, and apply Eternities Torment to help pet out. Then I med while the pet handles things, standing to apply Fear as needed. When it's a named mob pull, I usually mem up an additional dot or undead nuke to help the pet along. The spot labeled "B" is where I stand to pull "9". Since the mobs on the other side of the wall aggro easily, I stand inside so the mob runs away from the wall, before pulling him out. I then stand in spot "C" to pull 10 in a similar fashion. This seems to reduce the number of adds I get when pulling these spots. On difficult spawns that just won't split, I sometimes simply fear one, so it'll run out of aggro, so I can handle just the add mob single. With this method, and barring excessive resists, I can usually clear the whole ruin solo before the re-spawns. Hope this helps those of you who are looking to try this area for your first time.</font></td>

      </tr>

